body:
The bound method inside the guard method gets bound to `window` for some reason.

This fails:

```
var TestComponent = React.createClass({
    intervals: [],
    render: function() {
        return React.createElement("div");
    },
    setInterval: function setInterval(fn, ms) {
        this.intervals.push(setInterval(fn, ms));
    },
    componentDidMount: function() {
        this.setInterval(function () {
            console.log("hello");
        }, 1000);
    }
});

var testComponent = React.createElement(TestComponent, null);

React.render(testComponent, document.body);
```

with the error message:
`Uncaught TypeError: Cannot read property 'push' of undefined (index.js:7)`

I set a break point in `setInterval` and the first time it's called `this` is set to an instance of a react class.  It hit play and the method gets hit a second time and `this` is set to `window`.

Changing `setInterval: function setInterval(fn, ms) { ... }` to `setInterval: function (fn, ms) { ... }` fixes the issue.  This is code that's being generated by Babel so removing named functions is a little more work than just removing them from the source code.  It would be nice if React supported this syntax, but I don't know how much work is involved.
